<collectingCountry box="[980,1057,296,320]" name="Kenya" pageId="26" pageNumber="1568">Kenya</collectingCountry>
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[144,1104,168,575]" pageId="26" pageNumber="1568">
The butterflies are fairly constant in appearance, with very slight sexual dimorphism: the greyish-blue discal coloration of the male hindwing upperside is slightly more extensive than in females. Additionally, females lack preapical forewing streaks on the forewing upperside, whereas males usually have two, three or four such streaks. However, some males have only one streak – and occasionally, like the females, the apex is entirely black. In this regard the supposed near diagnostic difference between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharpe" authorityYear="1891" box="[144,325,519,543]" class="Insecta" family="Pieridae" genus="Belenois" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="1568" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="margaritacea">
<emphasis box="[144,325,519,543]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="1568">B. margaritacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the essentially allopatric 
<taxonomicName box="[675,794,519,543]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Pieris" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ericales" pageId="26" pageNumber="1568" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="raffrayi">
<emphasis box="[675,794,519,543]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="1568">B. raffrayi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not entirely reliable (cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Larsen TB" box="[144,283,551,575]" pageId="26" pageNumber="1568" refId="ref25550" refString="Larsen TB. 1996. The butterflies of Kenya and their natural history. 2 nd edn. Oxford (UK): Oxford University Press." type="book" year="1996">Larsen 1996</bibRefCitation>
, p.138). See also Discussion.
</paragraph>
